[2]
Date: Tue 18 Sep 2007
Source: BBC News [edited]
<http://news.bbc.co.uk/go/pr/fr/-/1/hi/uk/7000800.stm>

Tests on cattle at a 3rd Surrey farm have tested positive for FMD, it has
been confirmed. Livestock on the farm, which lies within an existing 3 km
(1.8-mile) protection zone in the Egham area, are being culled as a precaution.
The disease was confirmed in slaughtered cattle at 2 other farms in the
same area last week [10-16 Sep 2007].
Initial tests on pigs culled on a 4th farm in the same area tested negative
for FMD.
The 3 latest confirmed cases were just a few miles away from the Pirbright
research complex -- blamed as the source for the FMD outbreaks at 2 other
farms last month [August 2007].
The new cases are also believed to involve the same strain of the disease
found in the outbreaks last month [August 2007].
On Saturday [15 Sep 2007], the government's chief vet lifted a ban on
farmers across most of England from taking livestock to slaughter. But
livestock can still not be traded or moved for any other reason.
A full ban on any movement remains in place in the surveillance zone around
the 2 infected sites in Surrey [see comment].
A 3 km (1.8 mile) protection zone has been set up around the farmland, with
a 10 km (6.2 mile) surveillance zone encircling it.
--
